name: Gitano
description: The Gitano project is a git server which aims to keep everything in Git repositories, rather than using additional database stores.
contribution_justification: https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/contributing/
license_location_justification: https://git.gitano.org.uk/gitano.git/tree/COPYING
floss_license_justification: Everything is either BSD or CreativeCommons, see https://git.gitano.org.uk/gitano/debian.git/tree/copyright for an example
repo_distributed_justification: We use git, https://git.gitano.org.uk/
release_notes_vulns_justification: No publically known vulnerabilities at the time of update
report_process_justification:
Mailing list, mailto:gitano-dev@gitano.org.uk
IRC channel: gitano@freenode
Trello: https://trello.com/b/l4Id6iiC/gitano
report_archive_justification: Mailing list and trello (trello at https://trello.com/b/l4Id6iiC/gitano)
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: Thus far, no vulnerability reports have been received.
test_most_justification: Although coverage of testing is still being improved, coverage is good.
warnings_justification: Where C code is involved, warnings are enabled.
warnings_fixed_justification: During development, warnings are considered as errors.
warnings_strict_justification: During development, warnings are considered as errors.
know_secure_design_justification: Lead developer is aware of security design.
crypto_published_justification: The project outsources cryptographic operations to OpenSSH, SSL/TLS libraries, and GnuPG.
crypto_pfs_justification: PFS is a property of the SSH or TLS layers, not of Gitano.
crypto_password_storage_justification: We use Scrypt for storing passwords.
crypto_random_justification: Project does not create keys itself.
static_analysis_justification: No Static analysis tooling available for Lua
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: No such tool is available for Lua
dynamic_analysis_justification: No dynamic analysis tools of this kind exist for Lua code.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: No such tool is available for Lua
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: As above, no dynamic analysis tooling available.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: The project does not have a centralised CI, instead core developers must run package builds in order to create releases and those force the full test suites to run.
discussion_justification: Mailing list (gitano-dev@gitano.org.uk)
hardening_justification: Such mechanisms are usually not applicable to languages such as Lua
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff". // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: We do this by being in Debian.
build_reproducible_justification: Via Debian reproducible build effort.  As per https://tests.reproducible-builds.org/debian/rb-pkg/unstable/amd64/gitano.html our only issue is in an external tool (dblatex)
bus_factor_justification: This is met via the ability to recover the project from Daniel's cold dead hands - see https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/about/governance/
documentation_roadmap_justification: The project is mostly in a maintenance state.  The primary goals of the project listed at https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/about/goals/ are met.  Wider goals are ongoing and not contingent on the project per-se.
documentation_current_justification: The documentation is, for the most part, generated from the software.  As such, consistency is assured.
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: This is acceptable since the project is run essentially by one person and as such they do not have time or energy to devote to specific accessibility mechanisms.  Patches to improve accessibility will be assessed and merged where possible.
internationalization_justification: Gitano uses 'Tongue', an i18n library.  So far no localisations have been submitted.
sites_password_security_justification: The project does not store passwords of contributors or users and relies on SSH for authentication when the software is run.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Upgrade notes are in the `NEWS` file.
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio: No vulnerabilities have ever been reported in the software.
vulnerability_response_process_justifica: https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/contributing/ has a section about reporting security issues and vulnerabilities.
coding_standards_justification: This is done entirely by means of the review process documented at https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/contributing/
coding_standards_enforced_justification: There is no such tool for Lua
build_standard_variables_justification: Where we compile C code we honour compiler flags.  Mostly Lua code is built which does not need compilation.
build_non_recursive_justification: We do not use recursive make.
build_repeatable_justification: When built with appropriate flags, we are reproducible.  This is verified via Debian's reproducibility information.
installation_development_quick_justifica: By means of Debian packaging and the ability to run from a built tree (not installed)
external_dependencies_justification: Debian package dependency information, e.g. at https://git.gitano.org.uk/gitano/debian.git/tree/control
dependency_monitoring_justification: We believe that by means of relying on Debian's security processes, this will not be an issue for Gitano.
updateable_reused_components_justificati: All our dependencies come via the operating system - Debian.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: While this is not done on every checkin to master, it is done on any packaging release.
regression_tests_added50_justification: Where applicable, tests are adapted or added to expose an issue before a fix is committed.
test_statement_coverage80_justification: We use luacov and have reasonable coverage of over 95% in the libraries, and while the total coverage in the app is 76%, it is over 80% for the stated *supported* code, and over 90% in the core code.
implement_secure_design_justification: ACLs deny by default, the project developers consider security a critical component of design.
input_validation_justification: All inputs are filtered via SSH or similar to ensure trustworthiness.  Syntax of content is checked where appropriate before acting on it, and the policy of deny-by-default applies.
signed_releases_justification: Releases are uploaded to Debian which implies a full signed package of content.
version_tags_signed_justification: Releases are via Debian which as above implies signed content.
contributors_unassociated_justification: Contributions from others are detailed at https://git.gitano.org.uk/gitano.git/log/
copyright_per_file_justification: This is a requirement of submissions to the project.
license_per_file_justification: This is covered by a top level licence statement.
require_2FA_justification: Contribution occurs via SSH keys and those are locked by 2FA
secure_2FA_justification: 2FA for ssh keys is via yubikeys
two_person_review_justification: Review is always done by someone other than the author where possible, release cannot happen unless code is merged.
test_statement_coverage90_justification: Libraries have over 90% coverage, the main app has over 90% coverage in core areas.  Some plugins are less covered, but they are not supported content.
test_branch_coverage80_justification: Coverage calculators cover branches as well as lines.  Thus the above statement holds.
security_review_justification: We performed a security audit before the release of 1.0 and we consider security implications of every change.
assurance_case_justification: Trust boundaries are via SSH or a web service as per the installation instructions at https://wiki.gitano.org.uk/setup/system-user/ and as such the threat model is handled for us.

name: SignServer
description: Server-side application for digital signature creation.
contribution_justification:
As describe on https://www.signserver.org/contributors.html :
Contributors send patches to the mailing list.
contribution_requirements_justification:
As describe on https://www.signserver.org/contributors.html :
The file doc/DEVELOP.txt (https://svn.cesecore.eu/svn/signserver/trunk/signserver/doc/DEVELOP.txt) contains information about our coding guidelines:
We are loosely trying to follow the old Sun/Oracle Code Conventions for the 
Java TM Programming Language:
http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/documentation/codeconvtoc-136057.html

Some of the rules:
- The code should be properly indented
- We use spaces (not tabs) for indention, the IDE:s can be configured to use this
- Opening curly braces ("{") should not be on there own line. Example "if (true) {"
- First sentence in JavaDoc ends with a period ".". Example /** The signature algorithm. */
